title: danieleither
author: danieleither
content: I recently sold 2 x Antminer S17e units to a buyer on Ebay. Before selling I used these constantly for around 1.5 years with no issues or faults whatsoever, however the buyer is now having problems where the miners hash for around 2 hours before stopping. I asked him to send me the kernel logs, however I'm not familiar with the errors listed. I do note however that both error logs are very similar (which may suggest an external issue common to both miners, such as overheating or a problem with the mains supply).Can anyone shed some light? comments.author: philipma1957
comments.body: Looks like they shipped badly.You may have a total loss.I don’t know anyone that repairs the s17e.Your best case is the psu failed.Your worst case is the psu and the temp sensors failed .you need to very likely  take a return on them.

comments.author: BitMaxz
comments.body: Try to ask the buyer if the power source is 110v? Or if he has 220v? You can only run this unit on 220v lower than that the miner will not run properly.If not try to ask him to replug cables and the metal parts of PSU. There might be some shorted parts due to a loose heatsink. Thermal adhesive is the solution for loose heatsinks.

comments.author: mikeywith
comments.body: Quote from: danieleither on June 05, 2022, 11:20:01 AMCan anyone shed some light? I've had to drastically cut down the kernel log as the forum appears to have a 64000 character limit Post two different posts, cut the kernel in half, third or even quarter as needed, you didn't post the first half of the kernel log which is very important, but judging by the other half you posted, it seems that the miner might have a bad PSU, it could be dead, or the buyer's voltage is just way too low, you need to ask him for a proof that his voltage his 220v or even better, just ask him what voltage he runs them on.

comments.author: danieleither
comments.body: Quote from: philipma1957 on June 05, 2022, 12:38:21 PMLooks like they shipped badly.You may have a total loss.I don’t know anyone that repairs the s17e.Your best case is the psu failed.Your worst case is the psu and the temp sensors failed .you need to very likely  take a return on them.The buyer collected in person (2 months ago), and he had 4 units in total so I think we can rule out bad shipping. I've sold around 30 units so far, they are all sold on a collection-only basis (due to known issues shipping 17-series miners). As for temp sensors failing, I'd have to argue that it's not realistic that temp sensors on all 3 hashboards would fail simultaneously?As these were sold 2 months ago, I won't be accepting returns however I will do everything in my power to help the buyer. I do have some PSU's on order from Bitmain and I've agreed to send him one to try when they arrive. If it turns out to be two burned out PSU's I'll replace them FOC. In the meantime I'll ask the buyer if he is able to check his mains voltage. We are in UK where it's 240V mains, it's highly unlikely to be below 220v but I'll check this out

comments.author: philipma1957
comments.body: based on pick up info and that it worked 2 months my best guess is failed psu.

comments.author: mikeywith
comments.body: Quote from: philipma1957 on June 07, 2022, 01:48:29 PMbased on pick up info and that it worked 2 months my best guess is failed psu.Ya likely, but could be a few bad chips as well, also judging by the domain voltage error, could it be that he mixed and matched some hash boards? Can you get him to flash vnish firmware like awosomeminer or asic.to?This custom firmware eliminates a few possible causes and helps you narrow down the issue to one or two things.

comments.author: BitMaxz
comments.body: What I see are two different errors for PSU and Hashboard. I'm not an expert on repairing PSU but I have experience repairing them if the issue is PSU the always possible cause of broken PSU is Mosfet and if it's not giving enough power then capacitor. What I would like you to ask is to tell the buyer if he has a Multimeter I would like him to try to check the terminal if it's giving enough power only suggest this to check if flashing it with modded firmware as suggested above does not work. You can also suggest flashing it with BraiinsOS.

comments.author: mikeywith
comments.body: Quote from: BitMaxz on June 07, 2022, 11:53:54 PMWhat I would like you to ask is to tell the buyer if he has a Multimeter I would like him to try to check the terminal if it's giving enough power I do not think it is that easy with the s17 series PSUs, you only get 12v on the wire that powers the control board, the other side of the psu that feeds the busbar going into the hash boards only kicks when there is power draw from the hash board, so the simple testing procedure that works with other PSUs might be misleading with these psus.
